label chapter6:

    # [Scene: Municipal Hall | Late Afternoon]

    scene bg ch6_77428d_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm strings with a steady, hopeful pulse]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low murmur of voices, the soft patter of residual rain]
    "You step into the high, cool room with the outline of proposals and counterproposals still bright in your mind. The fluorescent light above picks out the salt in your hair and the smudges on your sleeve;"
    "the tablet in your apron is folded shut like a small, private ledger. For a moment the town compresses into a single breath—names, numbers, the smell of wet leather from the municipal chairs—and you wonder if"
    "any plan can hold against weather that never waits."
    "Your eyes find Ravi first. He is the picture of careful relief: sleeves rolled, tie loosened, a folder with stamps of approval catching the light. Marin stands near the long table, palms flat on the surface,"
    "watching the papers as if measuring their thickness against the shore. Lina's boots are planted ready, practical; Tom's hands are smeared with grease but steady on the back of her chair. Kai arrives with a camera"
    "slung low, his shirt smelling faintly of solder and seaweed from a long day of workshops."
    "The negotiation is not some one decisive speech; it is a dozen small, stubborn adjustments made at kitchen-table scale and signed in hallways. You breathe into that truth and let it steady you."
    show ravi_singh at left:
        zoom 0.7

    ravi_singh "The emergency stretch from the regional bond came through, but it's provisional. We have to show timely milestones—certification points for the modulars, measurable apprenticeship quotas, and a maintenance clause that ties local contractors to the schedule."
    show iris_alvarez at right:
        zoom 0.7

    iris_alvarez "We can do that. The apprenticeships were non-negotiable from our side. Whoever scales this has to take skilled hands with them—Tom's crew, Etta's garden coop, folks who've kept the pier alive."
    show marin_voss at center:
        zoom 0.7

    marin_voss "The memorandum reflects that. We specify staged certification—pilot sections, third-party review at each milestone, and penalties that revert funds if a private developer tries to buy the blueprint outright."
    "You notice Marin's fingers linger over their tablet. When your eyes meet, the nod that follows is small, almost standard-issue; but it lands with the weight of agreement. You allow yourself to read it as something"
    "more—an acceptance that the municipal machinery can be shaped, however slightly, to protect what people built."

    marin_voss "We can't promise aesthetics won't change entirely over time. But we can promise governance that keeps core community processes intact. That—' (they tap the corner of the memorandum) '—is what I can sign for."
    hide ravi_singh
    show lina_harrow at left:
        zoom 0.7

    lina_harrow "I'll fund and manage a dock-side maintenance corps. It keeps day-to-day operations running and gives people jobs. It also keeps this from becoming a showpiece for outside contractors."
    hide iris_alvarez
    show tomas_tom_alvarez at right:
        zoom 0.7

    tomas_tom_alvarez "And my shop can handle the standardized fittings. I'll expand hours and take on apprentices, but we set the terms—no exploitative subcontracting. If someone's going to build our future, they're going to learn it the way it's always been learned here."
    hide marin_voss
    show kai_nakamura at center:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_nakamura "And I'll keep documenting it. Open-source blueprints, real people in the photos—not promotional gloss. If others want to copy the tech, they copy the process too."
    "You watch the argument unfold—practicalities braided with principles. There are moments when you want to press harder, to demand ironclad guarantees. There are moments you notice Marin's jaw tighten, Ravi's eyes shift to budget lines, Lina's"
    "posture relax when job numbers are on the table. The accord forms like a patchwork: improvised pieces stitched with legal language."
    hide lina_harrow
    show iris_alvarez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    iris_alvarez "We ask for phased disbursement tied to public oversight committees. We keep our seedbanks and apprenticeships protected contractually. And the promenade reinforcement—core sections that preserve businesses—gets priority."
    "Ravi: (nodding) 'I'll draft the oversight language. The bond requires accountability; we get that and use it to keep the project community-led.'"
    "There is a pause—staff stepping into the room with copies, pens clicking. The act of signing feels ceremonial only because it marks the end of so many cold, sleepless nights. You pick up your pen, feeling"
    "the metal cool against your palm, the braided bracelet warm against your skin as if lending you steadiness."
    hide tomas_tom_alvarez
    hide kai_nakamura
    hide iris_alvarez

    scene bg ch6_77428d_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The soft scratch of pens; a distant gull calling through the open door]
    "Marin Voss signs, then looks up. Their eyes are a quiet harbor—measured, wary, and unexpectedly human. There's a flash of something like relief, almost regret for how much had to be bargained away, but it's there."
    "Ravi stamps the funds; Lina and Tom shake hands with an agreement that reads like a promise to the town's backbone. Kai Nakamura catches the moment on his camera, not as spectacle but as record."
    show kai_nakamura at left:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_nakamura "We did it. It feels—"
    show iris_alvarez at right:
        zoom 0.7

    iris_alvarez "Like a bridge that wasn't there before we started building it."
    show lina_harrow at center:
        zoom 0.7

    lina_harrow "Don't get soppy on me. We still have regulations to draft, contractors to vet, and storms to be paranoid about."
    hide kai_nakamura
    show tomas_tom_alvarez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    tomas_tom_alvarez "She's going to be soppy. Let her be soppy. She earned it."
    "For a beat the room softens. The plan is imperfect—noone pretends otherwise—but it is usable, accountable, and anchored by hands that know how to mend things. That seems to be the real win."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A gentle swell of strings; sunlight breaks through a thinning cloud outside]
    hide iris_alvarez
    hide lina_harrow
    hide tomas_tom_alvarez

    scene bg ch6_77428d_3 at full_bg
    "You step out into the evening, the city's air tasting of salt and toasted coffee from a vendor packing up for the night. The pile of work hasn't vanished; it has new scaffolding. You tuck the"
    "signed memorandum back into your apron, the paper now another tool in your bag. People drift back to their neighborhoods with phone calls and half-formed plans. You let your shoulders lower a degree you didn't know"
    "you were holding."
    # [Scene: Repaired Pier | Dusk]

    scene bg ch6_77428d_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Acoustic guitar with soft harmonies; the melody climbs gently]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Water lapping at the pylons, distant laughter, the creak of wood settling]
    "You find Kai Nakamura at the end of the repaired section—the very board where you used to carve initials in a heat younger than reckoning. He sits with his beanie pushed back, hair mussed, sleeves rolled,"
    "hands still carrying the day. He looks up when you step close, and his smile arrives like sunlight."
    show kai_nakamura at left:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_nakamura "You look like you could use a port in the storm."
    show iris_alvarez at right:
        zoom 0.7

    iris_alvarez "We're the port now, apparently."
    "He laughs, then reaches out. His hand finds yours, thumb pressing the braided bracelet you always twist when you're thinking. The contact is small but solid; it anchors the conversation that follows."

    kai_nakamura "I couldn't have pictured it all—this compromise, the municipal language, Lina signing on—but I did believe people would get up and help each other. Seeing it—' (he swallows, watching your face) '—it matters."

    iris_alvarez "It matters because people committed. It matters because we wrote protections into the paper instead of letting someone else write them into a market pitch."

    kai_nakamura "You stayed.—God, Iris, you stayed."
    "You want to unpack that, because 'staying' has been a compass and a burden in the same breath for you. You feel the memory of the pier festival lost in a storm—your grandmother's bent ring in"
    "your pocket like a small accusation—and you let the feeling pass through a grin you try to keep steady."

    iris_alvarez "I stayed because someone's got to make sure this town stays itself when the money comes. Someone's got to say no to prettified versions of our labor."

    kai_nakamura "And someone else has to take pictures of that 'no' and make it useful. We're a messy, stubborn pair, huh?"
    "You both laugh, and the sound is honest and free. The sea draws in a long breath and lets it go. Light from the promenade pools across wet planks, and you feel the pier respond like a living thing—stronger where it's been mended, flexible where it must bend."

    kai_nakamura "Can I—?"
    "You feel your chest unclench in that pressure. The knot of worry and exhaustion loosens as sunlight folds into the salt air. For once, progress is both political and personal: a memorandum signed, a maintenance crew"
    "agreed, a shop expanding—columns of practical hope—and then this small, intimate ceremony on the pier."

    kai_nakamura "We did a thing. And it's messy and it will be work forever, but—' (he grins) '—I like being messy with you."

    iris_alvarez "I like being stubborn for things that are worth sticking up for."
    "You talk longer—about apprenticeships, about the first pilot section due next month, about who'll be on the oversight committee and how you'll make sure Etta's garden stays right where it is. The conversation rolls and folds,"
    "the practical mingled with the tender. Kai asks questions about your plans for the next season; you ask him if he'll finally teach you to use manual settings on that camera. Each answer is a small"
    "promise."

    menu:
        "Press a kiss to his forehead":
            "You press a quick, warm kiss to his forehead. He laughs—soft and delighted—and leans his head against yours as if the sound itself settles into both of you."
        "Take his hand and squeeze":
            "You lace your fingers with his and squeeze. He returns the squeeze, eyes closed for a beat, the contact steady and simple, a promise without words."

    # --- merge ---
    "The small, ordinary intimacy is chosen and the world rearranges itself accordingly: the pier holds your weight; the work ahead hums like an engine you have already started. You think of apprentices arriving with lunch pails,"
    "of Tom's expanded hours, of Lina's steady crew working at dawn. Each is a stitch."
    "The sky moves from bruised lavender to deepening indigo. The first stars—sharp and sparse—blink awake over the harbor. You breathe in the salt and a faint sweetness of diesel and clove from the vendor's pack-down. The ache of sleepless nights remains, but it has softened to a patient afterglow."

    iris_alvarez "What do you think the town will look like in five years?"

    kai_nakamura "Rooftops green, kids knowing how to solder and plant in the same afternoon. A promenade that smells like coffee and seaweed and a little bit like old rope. People arguing in meetings but still bringing hot soup afterwards. Maybe that's naive."

    iris_alvarez "No—the right kind of naive. The kind that builds things."
    "He rests his forehead to yours again, and the moment feels less like a conclusion and more like the start of a long, steady project—two hands on a hammer, two eyes on the horizon."
    hide kai_nakamura
    hide iris_alvarez

    scene bg ch6_77428d_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Strings resolve into a warm, sustained chord; a soft wind chime pattern enters]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Gentle sea, distant municipal lights humming]
    "You are tired in a way that means you've done something important. You are bruised by compromise but buoyed by an accord that keeps the town's soul intact. The memorandum will be amended, the oversight committees"
    "will meet, the pilots will be rolled out with stumbles and triumphs. None of that is neat. None of it needs to be; it only needs to be alive."
    show kai_nakamura at left:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_nakamura "Are you ready to go home? Or do you want to sit here until the tide tells us to move?"
    "You consider the map of minutes and meetings waiting tomorrow, the list of contractors and the seed packets in your apron. You also consider the way his hand fits yours and the argument the two of you tacitly make with the sea—one of repair, not surrender."
    "You stand together as the pier hums beneath you. The town behind you is awake in a new, complicated way—tender and practical at once. You lean into Kai Nakamura, and the world, for tonight, feels held."
    hide kai_nakamura

    scene bg ch6_77428d_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Gentle coda, hopeful and sustained]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The sea, steady and patient]
    "You are tired, but you have risen. Not unscathed, but durable."

    scene bg ch6_77428d_7 at full_bg
    "THE END"
